{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> πλήν</b>, <br /> <i>Doric dialect</i>and <i>Aeolic dialect</i> <b>πλάν</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “SIG” 56.3(Argos, 5th c.BC), 421.7(Thermum, 3rd c.BC), “IG” 9(1).333.4 (_Locrian dialect_, 5th c.BC), “Berl.Sitzb.” 1927.158 (from Cyrene), “Schwyzer” 633.16, 19 (Eresus, 2nd-1st c.BC)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>preposition</i> with <i>genitive</i>, <b>except, save,</b> πάντων Φαιήκων πλήν γ᾽ αὐτοῦ Λαοδάμαντος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.207; τίς ἔτλη.. π. Ἡρακλῆο; 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Scutum Herculis” 74, compare 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 914, “IG” 12.6.108, etc.: with γε, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 909, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὑπεγγύους π. θανάτου liable to any punishment <b>short of</b> death, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 5.71 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἐπιτρέψαι περὶ σφῶν αὐτῶν π. θανάτου <b>save in respect of</b> death, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 4.54 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; σκυλεύειν τοὺς τελευτήσαντας π. ὅπλων of anything <b>save</b> their arms, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 469c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; διαρπάσαι.. ἐπέτρεψε πλὴν ἀνδραπόδων to carry off all plunder <b>save</b> slaves, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 2.4.27. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> later, <b>besides, in addition to,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX.Deu.18.8, 29.1. \">LXX</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__B</b></Level1> <i>conjunction</i>: <br /><Level2><b>__B.I</b></Level2> with single words and phrases, especially when a <i>negative</i> precedes, οὐκ ἆρ᾽ Ἀχαιοῖς ἄνδρες εἰσὶ π. ὅδ; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 1238; οὐκ οἶδα π. ἕν [prev. author] “OC” 1161, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Electra” 752; οὐ κάτοιδα π. ἐπὶ σμικρὸν φράσαι 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 414, compare 4th c.BC: Amphis Comicus 13 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: after a question implying a <i>negative</i>, τί σοι πέπρακται π.τεύχειν κακ; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 125, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 646: after πᾶς, etc., τὸ δ᾽ ἄρσεν αἰνῶ πάντα π. γάμου τυχεῖν 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 737; παντὶ δῆλον π. ἐμοί 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 529a, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 299, 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 12.19, etc.; νικᾶν.. πανταχοῦ.. ἔφυν π. εἰς σέ 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 1053 (πᾶς\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] is sometimes omitted, θνῄσκουσι [πάντες] π. εἷς τις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “OT” 118; ἀλλ᾽ ἔστι [πᾶσι] πλὴν σοί [prev. work] 370): frequently with ἄλλος (much like{ἤ}), τί οὖν μ᾽ ἄνωγας ἄλλο π. ψευδῆ λέγει; [prev. author] “Ph.” 100, compare “Aj.” 125, “Ant.” 236, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 106, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 1.2.1, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Protagoras” 334b, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: after a <i>comparative</i>, ταῦτ᾽ ἐστὶ κρείσσω π. ὑπ᾽ Ἀργείοις πεσεῖν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Heraclidae” 231, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Minos” 318e, etc.; πάντα μᾶλλον π. αὐτὸς ἅψασθαι 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.179 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: after a <i>superlative</i>, τὸ μέγιστον εἴργται π. αἱ τάξεις τοῦ φόρου [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Respublica Atheniensium” 3.5. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__B.II</b></Level2> frequently joined with other Particles: <br /><Level3><b>__B.II.1</b></Level3> π. εἰ, π. ἐάν, ὅταν, <br /><Level4><b>__B.II.1.a</b></Level4> followed by a Verb, π. εἴ τις κωμῳδοποιὸς τυγχάνει ὤν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Apologia” 18d, compare “Tht.” 177d, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 3.18, 10.39, etc.; π. ὅταν 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 260, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 293, etc.; π. εἰ ἄρα μή 1st c.BC-1st c.AD: Strabo Geographus 7.3.8; π. ἐὰν μὴ ἐξέλθῃ 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 554b2. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__B.II.1.b</b></Level4> with Verb omitted, οὐδεὶς οἶδεν.., π. εἴ τις ἄρ᾽ ὄρνις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 601, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 4.2.21, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; π. εἰ μή, after a <i>negative</i>, οὐδὲν προσδεησόμεθα, π. εἰ μὴ πάρεργόν τι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Politicus” 286d (variant); οὐδὲν ἂν πάθοι.., π. εἰ μή που κατὰ συμβεβηκός 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Generatione et Corruptione” 323b26; οὐ δεῖ.. τοῦτο.. κινεῖσθαι, π. εἰ μὴ κατὰ σ. [prev. author] “de An.” 406b8, compare “APr.” 43a39, 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “de Causis Plantarum” 1.10.6, 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis 4.74.—The pleonastic phrase π. εἰ μή is censured by 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Sol.” 7. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.II.2</b></Level3> πλὴν ἤ (where ἤ adds nothing to the sense; πλὴν εἰ is a common variant), οὐκ ἄλλῳ π. ἢ Προδίκῳ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 361, compare 734; οὐδὲν κάκιον.., πλὴν ἄρ᾽ ἢ γυναῖκες [prev. author] “Th.” 532, compare 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.111, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Apologia” 42a (variant{π. εἰ})\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also οὐ τὸν ἄνθρωπον ὑγιάζει π. ἀλλ᾽ ἢ.. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Metaphysica” 981a18 (variant). \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.II.3</b></Level3> π. οὐ <b>only</b> not, πάντες προσδέχονται, π. οὐχ οἱ τύραννοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Hiero” 1.18 (variant cited in 2nd c.AD: Athenaeus Epigrammaticus 4.144d), compare “Lac.” 15.6, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 18.45, 56.23, “Berl.Sitzb.” [prev. cited] \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.II.4</b></Level3> π. ὅτι <b>except</b> that.., <b>save</b> that.., καίτοι τί διαφέρουσιν ἡμῶν ἐκεῖνοι, π. ὅτι ψηφίσματ᾽ οὐ γράφουσι; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 1429; π. ἢ ὅτι 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 4.189 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πλήν γε ὅτι, πλήν γε δὴ ὅτι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 183a, “Phd.” 57b \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; after ὁμοίως, τὰ αὐτά, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Pelopidas” 4, 2nd c.AD: Artemidorus Daldianus Onirocriticus 1.56. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.II.5</b></Level3> π. ὅσον <b>except</b> or <b>save</b> so far as.., παρήκουσι παρὰ πᾶσαν [τὴν Λιβύην].., π. ὅσον Ἕλληνες.. ἔχουσι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.32, compare 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis 1.23; π. ὅσα 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 456a; π. καθόσον 2nd-3rd c.AD: Dio Cassius Historicus 72.19; π. καθόσον εἰ 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 6.88 codices \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__B.II.5.b</b></Level4> without a Verb, πάντων ἐρήμους, π. ὅσον τὸ σὸν μέρος <b>save</b> so far as thou art concerned, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1509 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τοὺς πολλοὺς ἀπέκτειναν π. ὅσον ἐκ τριῶν νεῶν οὓς ἐζώγρησαν <b>except</b> only.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 7.23, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 670a, 856d; ἀληθευτικός, π. ὅσα μὴ δι᾽ εἰρωνείαν 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Nicomachea” 1124b30. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__B.III</b></Level2> introducing a clause, mostly preceded by οὐδείς, πᾶς, ἄλλος, <b>save that,</b> νῦν δ᾽ οὐδεμία πάρεστιν.., π. ἥ γ᾽ ἐμὴ κωμῆτις ἥδ᾽ ἐξέρχεται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 5, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 41, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 1.8.20, etc.; οὐκ ἀντεξῄεσαν π. ἕως ἀκροβολισμοῦ 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 1.18.2 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: without any such word preceding, <b>only, albeit,</b> ἀπέπεμπε κήρυκας ἐς τὴν Ἑλλάδα, π. οὔτε ἐς Ἀθήνας οὔτε ἐς Λακεδαίμονα ἀπέπεμπε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.32, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1643, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 8.70, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Protagoras” 328e, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.III.2</b></Level3> to break off and pass to another subject, <b>only, however,</b> π. γνώριζε ἄτοπος ὤν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PCair.Zen.” 454.10 (3rd c.BC),compare 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 1.69.14, 2.17.1, NT.1Cor.11.11, 2nd c.AD: Diogenes Oenoandensis Epicureus 8, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Pericles” 34, etc.\">NT+3rd c.BC+</a>]: in late Prose, π. ἀλλά [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Pyrrh.” 5, 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Prom.” 20, “DMort.” 13.3, 20.4, etc.; π. ἀλλά γε [prev. author] “Rh.Pr.” 24. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__B.III.3</b></Level3> simply for δέ, <b>but,</b> πολλὴν στρατιὰν ἀθροίσας, π. ἄπειρον μάχης [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Herodianus Grammaticus 3.4.1; δυστυχῶν μέν, π. ἀλλ᾽ Ἑλλήνων 3rd c.AD: Heliodorus Scriptor Eroticus 6.7. (Cogn. with πλησίος, πελάζω, compare ἔμπλην.) \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]","strongNumber":"G4133","accentedUnicode":"πλήν","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G4119","matchingForm":"πλείων, πλεῖον","stepTransliteration":"pleiōn pleion","gloss":"greater","_zh_tw_Gloss":"多","_es_Gloss":"más grande","_zh_Gloss":"多"}],"shortDef":"but, however, only, yet","mediumDef":"but, however, only, yet <br />can function as an <i>improper preposition</i>, <b>besides, except,</b> <ref='Mrk.12.32'>Mk. 12:32</ref>; <ref='Act.8.1'>Acts 8:1;</ref> 20:23; as a <i>conjunction</i> <b>but, however, nevertheless,</b> <ref='Mat.18.7'>Mt. 18:7</ref>; <ref='Luk.19.27'>Lk. 19:27</ref>; <ref='Eph.5.33'>Eph. 5:33;</ref> equivalent to <greek>ἀλλά</greek>, <ref='Luk.6.35; 12:31'>Lk. 6:35; 12:31</ref>; <ref='Act.27.22'>Acts 27:22</ref>","stepGloss":"but/however","stepTransliteration":"plēn","count":32,"_es_Definition":"(1) conj. pero, todavía, no obstante, sin embargo ; (2) prep. con gen. excepto, pero, además ; excepto que, solo que (HCH.20:23; FIL.1:18)","_zh_tw_Definition":"1) 但是<br>2) 僅僅, 不過, 然而<br>3) 另一方面, 無論如何<br>4) 除了...以外","_zh_Definition":"1) 但是<br>2) 仅仅, 不过, 然而<br>3) 另一方面, 无论如何<br>4) 除了...以外","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"ngoại trừ; vậy nên; vì thế. Xem G4119","_zh_tw_Gloss":"然而","_es_Gloss":"pero/sin embargo","_zh_Gloss":"然而"}]}